  "prompt": "What is Islamic banking?",
  "response": "Islamic banking is a banking system that operates according to the principles of Islamic law (Sharia) and guided by Islamic economics. Key characteristics include:\n\n1. Prohibition of interest (riba)\n- No fixed interest rates on loans or deposits\n- Focuses on profit and loss sharing\n\n2. Ethical principles\n- Investments cannot support businesses considered unethical in Islam (alcohol, gambling, pork, etc.)\n- Emphasizes social responsibility and economic justice\n\n3. Risk-sharing\n- Banks and customers share financial risks and rewards\n- Promotes more collaborative financial relationships\n\n4. Key financial instruments\n- Mudarabah (profit-sharing partnership)\n- Musharakah (joint venture)\n- Murabaha (cost-plus financing)\n- Ijara (leasing)\n- Sukuk (Islamic bonds)\n\n5. Asset-backed financing\n- Transactions must be linked to tangible, productive economic activities\n- Discourages speculative financial practices\n\n6. Compliance\n- Overseen by Shariah boards to ensure adherence to Islamic principles\n- Different from conventional banking models\n\nIslamic banking aims to provide financial services consistent with Islamic religious principles while promoting economic development and social welfare.",
